<p><span class="scriptRef" com="scn" lang="eng" ref="mt+26:15">Matthew 26:15</span>. <strong> What are ye willing to give me! </strong> No indication of hesitation. Mark (<span class="scriptRef" com="scn" lang="eng" ref="mr+14:10">Mark 14:10</span>) says that he went ‘ <em> in order</em> that he might deliver him up to them.’
	</p>
<p style="margin-left:0.12em;"><strong> They weighed unto him. </strong> This, which is the correct sense, refers to the actual payment, which probably occurred on the night of the betrayal.
	</p>
<p style="margin-left:0.12em;"><strong> Thirty pieces of silver.</strong> Silver shekels, each worth a little more than two shillings, or fifty cents. The price was itself an insult, since this was the price for the life of a slave (<span class="scriptRef" com="scn" lang="eng" ref="ex+21:2">Exodus 21:2</span>). Our Lord died the death of a slave and a malefactor, that He might redeem us from the slavery and eternal misery of sin. Comp. <span class="scriptRef" com="scn" lang="eng" ref="zec+11:12">Zechariah 11:12</span>, here fulfilled. (Notice Joseph was sold for <em> twenty</em> pieces of silver. <span class="scriptRef" com="scn" lang="eng" ref="ge+37:28">Genesis 37:28</span>.) Some think that this was the <em> earnest money.</em> But Judas returned thirty pieces (chap. <span class="scriptRef" com="scn" lang="eng" ref="mt+27:3">Matthew 27:3</span>), and the answer then given him indicates that the rulers were done with him.
	</p>
